   360	
   361	Then, given the temperature of this room, T = 290 K, what values of
   362	(R,E,M) for the air in it do we expect to observe? By the Boltzmann law,
   363	it appears that the state of lowest energy will be overwhelmingly the
   364	most probable, because k is so small. Thus all the air in the room where
   365	I am writing this should be condensed into a small frozen puddle at the
   366	lowest point of the floor. Evidently, the prediction has ignored
   367	something of crucial importance for the inference.
   368	
   369	J. Willard Gibbs (1875, 1902), showed how to correct this. We introduce
   370	a new quantity, a function S(R,E,M) of the macroscopic state and define
   371	the \"free energy\" $F = E-TS$. Then we modify Boltzmann's rule by
   372	taking the probability of the state (R,E,M) proportional to
   373	$\exp(-F/kT)$.
   374	
   375	Given T, the most probable state is the one that minimizes F. We now
   376	find that the corrected rule gives us, at all temperatures and to the
   377	accuracy of our best measurements, a quantitatively correct prediction
   378	of the condition of the air in this room. The new quantity S that has
   379	rescued us from being eternally frozen and immobile is called entropy.
